[{"id":"VH908313","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><include href=\"../Passage/VH908249.qti.xml\" xmlns:xi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude\"></include></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">In which switch position, open or closed, can the current be the same in the left and right branches, and why?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VH908313_rubric","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<div class=\"stimulus_reference\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents a circuit that contains a battery, a switch, a capacitor, and three resistors. A current is also indicated on the circuit. The left side contains a battery. Below the battery is a resistor labeled 5 ohms. Above the battery, is an upward pointing current labeled 0.5 amp. Moving up the left side and across the top, the circuit splits into two vertical branches. The first vertical branch has an open switch labeled S, a capacitor labeled 5 microfarads, and a resistor labeled 10 ohms. The second vertical branch has a resistor labeled 10 ohms.\" height=\"160\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VH908249.g02.png\" width=\"210\" /></div>\n\n<div class=\"passage\">\n<div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<p class=\"passage_para\">In the circuit shown above, the switch <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"S\"><math alttext=\"S\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mstyle><mrow><mstyle mathvariant=\"normal\"><mrow><mi>S</mi></mrow></mstyle></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> is open, the capacitor is uncharged, and the current through the battery is <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"0.5 amp\"><math alttext=\"0.5 amp\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mrow><mn>0.5</mn><mtext>â€‰</mtext><mstyle mathvariant=\"normal\"><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow></mstyle></mrow></math></span></span>.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n"}],"choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Neither position, because the resistors in these branches have different resistances.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Both positions, because the current in the middle branch will be zero at some time for both positions.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Only when the switch is open, because then the resistors are in series.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Only immediately after the switch is closed, because then the equivalent resistance of the middle and right branches equals that of the left branch.</p>"],"answer":1}]